<Layout
  title="New Home Windows: Materials, Types, Glazing & Prices (Australia)"
  description="Aluminium vs uPVC vs timber, awning vs sliding vs casement, U-values explained, plus Wideline, Stegbar and price lists. A buyer's guide for new-build owners."
>
  <div class="win">

    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <div class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo; <span>Building Materials</span> &rsaquo; <span>Windows</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Page header -->
    <div class="win-header">
      <h1>New Home Windows</h1>
      <p class="win-lead">Frame materials, window types, glazing, U-values and pricing — what to ask your builder before you accept the standard inclusion.</p>
      <div class="win-meta">
        <span>11 topics</span>
        <span class="sep">·</span>
        <span>Last updated 4 April 2026</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Intro -->
    <div class="intro-box">
      <p>Windows are a very important aspect of a home and careful consideration should be taken before accepting whatever a builder provides as standard. Typically builders won't tell you about the options that are available and simply provide the minimum required to comply with local regulations. They contribute to aesthetics, airflow, soundproofing, heating, cooling and privacy.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Key Takeaways -->
    <div class="takeaways">
      <div class="takeaways-title">Key Takeaways</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Frame material matters more than you think.</strong> uPVC is the most thermally efficient, thermally broken aluminium and timber are close behind, and standard aluminium performs poorly from a thermal perspective and contributes significantly to the heating and cooling load of a home.</li>
        <li><strong>Residential frames cap out around 2.34m.</strong> Doors and windows above 2.34m might not be possible with standard residential frames — you may be forced to upgrade to commercial frames. Check the manufacturer's website for hard limits.</li>
        <li><strong>Awning, casement and tilt-and-turn form a full seal — sliding windows can't.</strong> Sliding windows have a small gap in the middle and can't form a tight seal, costing you in air infiltration, sound and thermal loss.</li>
        <li><strong>Single-glazed aluminium rarely gets below U-value 3, even with double glazing and low-e.</strong> Thermally broken frames can easily reach 1.5. A lot of people spend money going from single glazing (U≈6) to double glazing (U≈3.6) — good, but not great.</li>
        <li><strong>Windows over 80kg may need onsite glazing — budget $500+ per window.</strong> Large windows and doors may also require craning, which adds another significant cost. Factor weight and access into your design decisions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

