      <!-- Glass Types -->
      <div class="card" id="glass-types">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Glass Types: Low-E, Laminated, Acoustic &amp; Viridian Options</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <p>It's very difficult for a single glazed window, no matter the treatment applied or the thickness, to come close to a double glazed window in terms of thermal efficiency. Many factors go into a double glazed window:</p>

          <div class="cost-list">
            <div class="cost-row"><span class="cost-label">Thickness of the 2 glass planes</span><span class="cost-value">&mdash;</span></div>
            <div class="cost-row"><span class="cost-label">Type of windows used</span><span class="cost-value">&mdash;</span></div>
            <div class="cost-row"><span class="cost-label">Gap between the window panes</span><span class="cost-value">&mdash;</span></div>
            <div class="cost-row"><span class="cost-label">Argon or other insulating gas used</span><span class="cost-value">&mdash;</span></div>
          </div>

          <p>Viridian is one of the main glass suppliers in Australia and has multiple products that can be considered for your use case. Low-e windows are common and make a significant difference compared to standard clear windows. They come in two forms — soft coated and hard coated — which differ in how they're manufactured and where they can be used.</p>

          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Soft coated Low-E</div>
              <ul>
                <li>Must be incorporated into a double glazed unit — the coating is less durable than a hard coated (pyrolytic) coating when exposed to the atmosphere.</li>
                <li><strong>Cannot</strong> be glazed in single glazed applications.</li>
                <li>Has a shelf life and will begin to break down if stored too long without being incorporated into double glazed units.</li>
                <li>Products like Viridian <strong>LightBridge™</strong> or <strong>PerformaTech™</strong> have significantly lower U-values than hard coated pyrolytic types.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Hard-coated Low-E</div>
              <ul>
                <li>Manufactured online during the float manufacturing process (soft coats are applied offline some time after the glass is made).</li>
                <li>Pyrolytic coatings have a long shelf life.</li>
                <li>Can be used in single glazed applications — products like <strong>ComfortPlus™</strong> and <strong>EnergyTech™</strong>.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Types of Low-e (diagram)</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/windows/types-of-low-e-glass.png" alt="Types of Low-e glass" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Single-pane Low-e caveat</div>
              <p>Single pane Low-e glass has the coating on the inside, which can be difficult to maintain as a clear window — owners have reported visibility and cleaning issues over time.</p>
              <p style="font-size: 12px; color: #888; margin: 8px 0 0 !important;">
                Source: <a href="https://www.viridianglass.com/resources/faqs/energy/what-is-the-difference-between-hard-coated-and-soft-coated-low-e-glass/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Viridian — Hard vs Soft coated Low-e glass</a>
                · <a href="https://www.productreview.com.au/listings/oceania-glass" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ProductReview — Oceania Glass</a>
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

