      <!-- Thermally Broken Frames -->
      <div class="card" id="thermally-broken">
        <div class="card-head">
          <h3>Thermally Broken Window Frames</h3>
          <span class="badge-cost">Up to +40% vs standard</span>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
          <div class="compare-2">
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">What it is</div>
              <p>Double glazing is important and it will reduce the chance of condensation forming and provide thermal insulation. However if the frames aren't thermally broken then there will be a transfer of heat or cold through the frame which can cause condensation on the frame and lower overall performance. Think of a thermally broken window as having an insulating material in the middle of the frame stopping the transfer of heat/cold.</p>
              <p>This is more of an issue in aluminium windows. Timber and uPVC window frames aren't impacted significantly by this.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-col">
              <div class="compare-label">Thermally broken detail</div>
              <figure><img src="/images/windows/thermally-broken-window.png" alt="Thermally broken window frame" loading="lazy"></figure>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="box-info">
            Thermally broken frames are more likely to have benefits in climates with temperatures under 5°C but this needs further investigation in your circumstance.
          </div>

          <div class="box-warn">
            <strong>Cost can be significant.</strong> There are cases where it's 40% more and many manufacturers don't have them as an option.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

